States, looking at new and canonized horror texts by Nalo Hopkinson, NK Jemisin, Gloria Naylor, and Chesya Burke. These Black women fiction writers take advantage of horror's ability to highlight U.S. white dominant cultural anxieties by using Africana folklore to revise horror's semiotics within their own imaginary. Ultimately, Brooks compares the legacy of Shakespeare's Sycorax (of The Tempest) to Black women writers themselves, who, deprived of mainstream access to self-articulation, nevertheless influence the trajectory of horror criticism by forcing the genre to de-centralize whiteness and maleness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican American women authors. 0aAfrican American women in literature. 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aFeminist theory. 0aHorror in literature. 0aHorror tales, AmericanxSpecimensx21st century. 0aHorror tales, Americany21st centuryvSpecimens. 0aWomen authors, BlackxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen, BlackvFiction. 0aWomen, BlackxFiction. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aEngland.  aafrican literature.  aafrican.  adiaspora.  ahaiti.  ahorror fiction.  ahorror.  ajamaica.  aliterature.  ashakespeare.  atempest.  atrinidad.  awomen.1 aBrooks, Kinitra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066609040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813584645zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813584645423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813584645.jpg  a978-3-11-066609-0  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL